# Defining the data for various preprocessing part
def preprocess_text(text):
  if isinstance(text, str):
    # Lowercase the text
    text = text.lower()

    # Remove URLs
    text = re.sub(r'http\S+', '', text)

    # Remove special characters, numbers, and punctuations (except for @ and #)
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-z#@]', ' ', text)

    text = re.sub(r'@[A-Za-z0-9]+', '', text)   # Remove mentions

    text = re.sub(r'#', '', text)  # Remove hashtags

    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()  # Remove extra whitespaces

    text = re.sub(r'\b[\w\-.]+?@\w+?\.\w{2,4}\b', '', text)  # Remove email ids

    text = re.sub(r'@\w+', '', text) # Remove usernames

    text = re.sub(r'\b\w{1,2}\b', '', text) # Remove short words


    return text

def remove_stopwords(tokens):
    if tokens is not None:
        return [word for word in tokens if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    else:
        return []

def train_word2vec(tokens, vector_size):
    model = Word2Vec(sentences=tokens, vector_size=vector_size, window=5, min_count=1, workers=4)
    return model

# Defining the function to generate the  word embeddings
def generate_word_embeddings(tokens, word2vec_model):
    embeddings = []
    for token in tokens:
        if token in word2vec_model.wv:
            embeddings.append(word2vec_model.wv[token])
        else:
            embeddings.append(np.zeros(vector_size)) 
    return embeddings

Building Bidirectional GRU model¶

In [85]:
# Defining the Bidirectional GRU model
vector_size = 100  
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word2vec_model.wv) + 1, vector_size))
for word, i in tokenizer.word_index.items():
    if word in word2vec_model.wv:
        embedding_matrix[i] = word2vec_model.wv[word]

model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(len(word2vec_model.wv) + 1, vector_size, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=max_sequence_length, trainable=False))
model.add(Bidirectional(GRU(128, return_sequences=True))) 
model.add(Bidirectional(GRU(64)))  
model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))  
model.add(Dropout(0.5)) 
model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))

for i, param_set in enumerate(parameters, 1):
    print(f"Iteration {i}:")
    print("Hyperparameters:", param_set)

    # Defining the model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Embedding(len(word2vec_model.wv) + 1, 100, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=max_sequence_length, trainable=False))
    model.add(Bidirectional(GRU(param_set["gru_units"], return_sequences=True)))
    model.add(Bidirectional(GRU(param_set["gru_units"])))
    model.add(Dense(param_set["dense_units"], activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(param_set["dropout_rate"]))
    model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))

In [184]:
def get_top_embedding_features(model, tokenizer, num_features=2):
    # Getting the weights of the embedding layer
    embedding_weights = model.layers[0].get_weights()[0]

    # Getting the word index and calculating the norms of the vectors
    word_index = tokenizer.word_index
    embedding_norms = np.linalg.norm(embedding_weights, axis=1)

    # Getting the indices of the top features with the highest norms and initialize a list to store top features and weight
    top_features_indices = np.argsort(embedding_norms)[-num_features:]
    top_features = []

    # Populate the list with top features and their weights
    for index in top_features_indices:
        word = list(word_index.keys())[list(word_index.values()).index(index)]
        weight = embedding_norms[index]
        top_features.append((word, weight))

    return top_features

# Call the function and print the top features
top_embedding_features = get_top_embedding_features(model, tokenizer)
print("Top Features with the Highest Weights:")
for feature in top_embedding_features:
    print(f"Feature: {feature[0]}, Weight: {feature[1]:.4f}")

# Perform K-fold cross-validation
for fold, (train_index, val_index) in enumerate(kf.split(X_padded), 1):
    print(f"Fold {fold}/{n_splits}:")

    # Split the data into train and validation sets
    X_train_fold, X_val_fold = X_padded[train_index], X_padded[val_index]
    y_train_fold, y_val_fold = y_categorical[train_index], y_categorical[val_index]

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    # Train the model
    history = model.fit(X_train_fold, y_train_fold, epochs=1, batch_size=64, verbose=0)

    # Evaluate the model on training data
    train_loss, train_accuracy = model.evaluate(X_train_fold, y_train_fold, verbose=0)
    print("Training Accuracy:", train_accuracy)
    fold_train_accuracy.append(train_accuracy)

    # Evaluate the model on validation data
    val_loss, val_accuracy = model.evaluate(X_val_fold, y_val_fold, verbose=0)
    print("Validation Accuracy:", val_accuracy)
    fold_val_accuracy.append(val_accuracy)

# Calculate average accuracy across all folds
avg_train_accuracy = sum(fold_train_accuracy) / n_splits
avg_val_accuracy = sum(fold_val_accuracy) / n_splits
print("\nAverage Training Accuracy:", avg_train_accuracy)
print("Average Validation Accuracy:", avg_val_accuracy)
